props.ssml: Do you know what a wrinkle is?
When the Fiber orientation in the laminate is disturbed out of plane either positive or negative it is called a wrinkle.

Let's look at two major types of wrinkles. 
Transversal and Longitudinal.
Wrinkles which are parallel to the blade axis up to 30° are called longitudinal wrinkle. These do not affect the structural strength of the laminate.
Wrinkles which are perpendicular to the blade axis between 30°- 90° are called transversal wrinkles. These affect the structural strength of the laminate, and are also called blade killers.

We could learn all the theory around wrinkle inspection.. but what will we do without the tools used for the purpose.
Tools help us to inspect wrinkles accurately and make justified conclusions. We could look at the tools from two perspectives.
Those used for inspection and those which aid in the inspection process.
Protractor, Vernier Caliper, Wrinkle Gauge and Measuring Tape are called Inspection tools.
Flashlight, Microtip Pencil, Camera, Permanent Marker, Millimeter paper and QCIF format, aid the inspection process.
Reeding from analog devices must be read perpendicular to the instrument’s scale to avoid measurement variation due to parallax effect.
All units are measured in millimeters unless otherwise specified.
Can you see some tools lying on the table. Click on them to explore their functions
A flashlight is a portable hand-held electric light, used to illuminate the wrinkle area.
A protractor is a measuring tool, used to measure wrinkle angles.
A wrinkle gauge is used to replicate the profile of the wrinkle on millimeter paper.
Millimeter Paper as a graph to trace the wrinkle profile.
The Calculator is used for wrinkle ratio calculation based on height and width of wrinkle
A Microtip pencil has a fine lead and is used to trace the wrinkles on millimeter paper.
A marker pen is used for marking the wrinkle on laminate for repair purpose
A Vernier Caliper is used to accurately measure the width and height of the wrinkle when cannot be read from millimeter paper
QCIF Format is used for documenting wrinkle data.
Measuring tape is used for measuring linear measurements on wrinkle position

We have learnt about the types of wrinkles, but while you are at the blade laminate, how do you actually begin to look for them. Let us look at some of these aspects. Click on the picture to know more
Inspect the shell/web inner/outer surface according to general control instruction respectively
Detect the positive bump or negative depression on the laminate by carefully looking at shadow created by wrinkle
Detect the area with dark resin colour without any visible bump or depression indicating inner laminate wrinkle
Inspect the main laminate and detect the area with depression or bump in the shape of knee mark, foot marks or round marks etc.
Inspect the laminate and detect the area with step wrinkles caused by embossed mould mark or by silicone profile top inlay in web moulding process
Inspect the core material area (especially close to L T/T E and main laminate) for step wrinkle caused by balsa panel offset or raised balsa blocks
Confirm the bump depression by moving your hand along the surface. If noticeable steps observed conclude the area with wrinkle
Inspect at infusion support plate area and look for any depression
Inspect under the infusion profile joints/ pressure plate for possible positive/ negative wrinkle
Inspect at infusion support plate area and look for any imprint depth at the tip
Inspect L E and T E flange area and look for flange wrinkle and offset between flange segments
Inspect the main laminate and reinforcement laminate area and look for visible step at start and end of plies
Inspect the non main laminate area and look for visible step at the start and end of non main laminate layers
Inspect the stitching area and look for the in-plane wrinkle where it was not stitched according to BSG or general guide
Inspect the glass start and end area and look for transversal layer stretch where length of fibre orientation disturbance exceeds limitations specified in AC – zero zero zero two six

To find the wrinkle you have to inspect the laminate area visually and by moving your hand along the surface.
If you find any noticeable wrinkle the next step would be to measure it. 
In this section, we will try to understand how the wrinkle is measured.

Wonderful, You just built an understanding on wrinkle measurement. Remember that  good ability to measure a wrinkle correctly comes from practical on ground experience of identifying and measuring wrinkles in many situations. So keep practicing..
while measuring a wrinkle it is important to first decide what type of wrinkle it is. Measuring the angle of the wrinkle is helpful in understanding this.
Any wrinkle located at an angle between 0-30 degrees or (less than equal to 30 degrees) from the blades axis is considered as longitudinal wrinkle and need not be repaired.
Any wrinkle located at an angle between  30°- 90° from the blade axis is considered as transversal wrinkle and must be evaluated further to decide for repair.
Flange Wrinkles are accepted up to 60° from the blade axis.
Place origin point of the protractor at start point of the wrinkle and adjust the protractor baseline parallel to the UID direction or stitching line in biaxial.
Read the angle of the wrinkle either from inner scale or from outer scale depending on the direction of wrinkle.
If the angle is more than requirement mentioned in AC-00026 for that type of wrinkle, then the height and width of the wrinkle will have to be measured.
Direction of UD layers or stitching lines in biaxial layers along the blade axis is referenced at 0° for angle measurement.

The wrinkle gauge is a very important tool to get the correct measurement of a wrinkle. Do not use the gauge if steel pins are missing or pins are bent or overlapped.
Click on each point to learn about various aspects of the wrinkle gauge.
Before measuring wrinkle size make sure all the steel pins are aligned in a straight line by pushing all the pins towards a flat surface.

When applying the wrinkle Gauge make sure the gauge is placed 90 degrees to the laminate and parallel to fiber roving's direction. (UD layers or blade axis / Biaxial stitching line) in order to avoid measurement variation
Before measurement mark the "most serious spot" using a permanent marker on the laminate. The most serious spot is the location where the maximum height or steepest point is observed on the wrinkle
When measuring wrinkle make sure all the pins are pushed towards the laminate in order to get the exact wrinkle profile on the marked area.

Let us learn the method of measuring wrinkle height and width.
Mark the point on the horizontal line.
Count number of lines in the millimeter paper to evaluate height of wrinkles.
If Mark is between two lines use of calliper to determine the height.

Mark start and endpoint of the wrinkle (on the same horizontal line) in the millimetre paper.
Count number of vertical line separately from step point to start and endpoint of the wrinkle or use vernier caliper to measure the wrinkle width.
The shortest distance from steep point is considered as the wrinkle width .

Mark the wrinkle start point.
 Count number of vertical lines from wrinkle start point to steep point of the wrinkle, or use vernier caliper to measure width.
The distance is considered as wrinkle width .

If the wrinkle has a flat top the edge of top needs to be considered in order to calculate wrinkle width.
 The edge which provides shortest width needs to be considered for width calculation.

This brings us to the end of the training session. 
Let us look at some of our key learnings
When the fibre orientation of a laminate is disturbed out of plane, it is called a Wrinkle.
Visual inspection of the wrinkle helps to identify wrinkle defects

Tools used for wrinkle measurement primarily include flash light , protractor, vernier caliper, wrinkle gauge, M M paper and QCIF format. All units are measured in millimeters unless specified otherwise.
It is mandatory to use the flashlight for wrinkle inspection
Different types of wrinkles are categorised based on their appearance and location. Acceptance criteria may vary for each type of wrinkle
while inspecting the wrinkle pay special attention to areas with depressions, leading edge and trailing edge , flange area, areas under infusion profile and core material areas.

Ensure that you use the correct method for measuring the wrinkle angle, using the wrinkle gauge, transferring the wrinkle, measuring the height and width of the wrinkle and calculating the wrinkle ratio.
You can now view your score on the screen.
You can also repeat this training session by clicking on Start again.
